He returned to Rome in 194 to enjoy a splendid triumph. For the rest of his life he was employed chiefly on diplomatic business concerning Greece and the East. One of his embassies was to Prusias, king of Bithynia, to call on him to surrender Hannibal, who was living at his court in advanced old ageÍ¾ this led to Hannibal's suicide. Flamininus was censor in 189 (see below, 42), and lived on till some time after 167, in which year he became augurÍ¾ but the date of his death is unknown.
